it's gonna
start getting interested.

31:35.433 --> 31:38.200
Bears, wolves, they don't mind
eating rotten food.

31:38.267 --> 31:39.500
And I just put up
the dinner bell.

31:47.833 --> 31:49.567
Just gonna be continuing
the process

31:49.633 --> 31:52.000
of getting all
of the rotten goods.

31:54.167 --> 31:55.667
Even though we're getting
it in the water

31:55.733 --> 31:57.267
so it distils the scent,

31:57.333 --> 31:58.967
it's gonna go downstream.

31:59.033 --> 32:01.467
There's no way
they won't smell it.

32:01.533 --> 32:03.367
That's why
once I start this I gotta,

32:03.433 --> 32:04.600
the fact that I opened 'em up

32:04.667 --> 32:06.333
and looked at it today,
I got to finish it today.

32:07.700 --> 32:08.800
Boom.

32:08.867 --> 32:09.967
Boom.

32:17.000 --> 32:19.000
SUE: I'm gonna get up on top.

32:19.067 --> 32:21.367
It was a little chilly,
so I threw on my sweatshirt.

32:26.833 --> 32:28.767
And we've
got a wolf on the runway.

32:28.833 --> 32:30.367
That's the area
I got to go to,

32:30.433 --> 32:31.933
that's the area
the wolf is at.

32:32.367 --> 32:35.033
Looks to me maybe
a juvenile female wolf

32:35.100 --> 32:39.067
on the runway, headed towards
where I had to dump
all that food.

32:39.133 --> 32:41.433
Little wolfie
on the spot there.

32:41.500 --> 32:42.667
Wolves are a pack animal.

32:42.733 --> 32:44.433
They don't
generally travel alone.

32:44.800 --> 32:46.433
Doesn't mean
they're not there.

32:46.500 --> 32:50.533
Not even 30 minutes
from when I tossed
the last rotten biscuit out,

32:51.200 --> 32:53.233
and here's a wolf.
Boom! On it.

32:53.600 --> 32:55.067
And that's exactly
what we were hoping,

32:55.133 --> 32:56.767
is get everything
away from camp.

32:57.300 --> 32:59.833
Now imagine
if I had families here
with little kids and

32:59.900 --> 33:03.367
your predator-human
interaction is,
is right there.

33:03.433 --> 33:04.633
That's how quick
it can happen.

33:04.700 --> 33:07.400
Nine times out of 10
the interaction with a wolf,

33:07.467 --> 33:09.033
I'll go out there and he'll...

33:09.100 --> 33:11.133
It'll get skid away
and then come back in.

33:11.200 --> 33:16.133
If it were a whole pack, I'd,
I'd probably just hold off
on my activities now.

33:18.800 --> 33:22.767
The sun doesn't set
so that works in my favour.
I'll just be tired and sore.

33:25.933 --> 33:27.833
CHIP: You know I want
to show my kids every season.

33:27.900 --> 33:30.933
And there's a different skill
and a different way
of doing things each time.

33:36.467 --> 33:38.267
Just making heart
and tongue soup.

33:38.333 --> 33:40.333
CHIP: This is the first meal
usually off of an animal.

33:40.400 --> 33:42.000
The tongue and the heart

33:42.067 --> 33:44.600
are organs that are small,

33:44.667 --> 33:46.733
full of fat,
really good tasting,

33:46.800 --> 33:49.167
different kind
of quality of meat.

33:49.233 --> 33:50.933
Throw some potatoes
and an onion in there.

33:52.000 --> 33:54.067
Now we can let this
all cook for quite a while.

33:54.133 --> 33:55.967
And then for dessert,
my wife and my daughters

33:56.033 --> 33:57.067
picked a bunch of mushua.

33:57.700 --> 33:59.867
We've had an all-around
profitable day, I'd say.

33:59.933 --> 34:01.867
Ladies really socked it in
with the food

34:01.933 --> 34:03.567
and it's gonna be a big,
hearty meal.

34:03.633 --> 34:05.000
And it's by their own hands.

34:05.333 --> 34:07.100
The girls may not have
shot the caribou

34:07.167 --> 34:08.467
but they helped work him,
and drag him,

34:08.533 --> 34:10.833
and participated in everything
but pulling the trigger.

34:11.433 --> 34:13.233
This is like food
of the season to us.

34:13.300 --> 34:15.167
This is kind of like having
turkey for Thanksgiving,

34:15.567 --> 34:17.267
or having a ham at Christmas.

34:17.333 --> 34:19.433
-Pretty good, eh?
-Pretty good.

34:19.500 --> 34:22.533
CHIP: Yep. We've got firewood,
so we've got heat.

34:22.600 --> 34:24.000
We got our tents up.

34:24.067 --> 34:25.667
We got uh, meat.

34:26.633 --> 34:29.500
Now we're secure.
We've got all the basic things
we need.

34:29.567 --> 34:31.867
The best thing is that
some day when me
and your mom aren't here,

34:31.933 --> 34:34.500
you girls know how to do
all of this, no matter what
the job is.

34:35.267 --> 34:37.800
And the best part
of that is that you get
all hands-on experience.

34:37.867 --> 34:39.367
We don't just sit there
and tell 'em what we've done,

34:39.433 --> 34:41.600
we talk about
what we've all done,
and done together.

34:41.667 --> 34:44.100
It's adventure,
it's family time,

34:44.167 --> 34:45.667
it's just, uh, being together.

34:48.633 --> 34:51.200
CHIP: We're in the right spot.
We're at this spot
for a reason.

34:51.467 --> 34:55.233
This is uh, this is home
to us.
We keep coming back here.

34:55.300 --> 34:57.100
Nothing like Kiwalik, yeah?

34:57.167 --> 34:58.467
Nothing like Kiwalik.

34:59.067 --> 35:00.833
(ALL CHUCKLING)

35:05.300 --> 35:08.833
GLENN: You have to learn
the cycles and the times
where things are happening

35:08.900 --> 35:10.833
so that you can take advantage
of the opportunities.

35:21.867 --> 35:24.733
In the spring when the lake
starts to melt, it's the time
of year when the ducks

35:24.800 --> 35:27.967
are gonna be concentrated
along the shoreline because
they got no wheres else to go.

35:28.033 --> 35:29.567
Ducks need water,
and this is where it is.

35:30.300 --> 35:31.967
Right in this moat
along the shoreline.

35:33.267 --> 35:35.233
But conditions
are changing fast.

35:35.300 --> 35:37.000
With that sun beating
down on the ice today,

35:37.500 --> 35:38.967
it'll get up in the 70s.

35:39.033 --> 35:40.433
And the lake ice
right along the edge,

35:40.500 --> 35:42.667
the moat's getting wider,
it's starting to break up.

35:42.733 --> 35:45.167
Little pieces are breaking
off when the breeze blows.

35:46.033 --> 35:47.300
It's gonna change real fast.

35:47.733 --> 35:50.567
If a breeze comes up,
this can all disappear
in one day.

35:57.433 --> 36:00.533
I see four so far.

36:00.600 --> 36:02.633
Let's see if I can get close
enough to get a shot.

36:12.633 --> 36:13.767
(SHOT FIRED)

36:21.033 --> 36:22.033
(GUN SHOT)

36:24.233 --> 36:25.700
I hit one.

36:29.767 --> 36:33.000
I shot, it took off,
and I kept shooting

36:33.067 --> 36:35.167
when they were in the air
and got one of 'em.

36:35.567 --> 36:37.267
Thankfully a breeze
blew the duck back in,

36:37.333 --> 36:40.100
but it got hung up in some
grass out here off the shore.

36:41.500 --> 36:43.900
The bottom here
is really soft and muddy,

36:43.967 --> 36:46.700
so I'm gonna make something
to throw out there
and retrieve the duck.

36:47.933 --> 36:49.933
I don't want to walk out there
and get stuck in the mud.

36:54.167 --> 36:55.667
Here we go.

36:55.867 --> 36:57.933
We'll see what happens.
It might work.

36:58.000 --> 36:59.367
I might be able
to throw it that far,

36:59.433 --> 37:00.567
I'll see. I don't know.

37:03.833 --> 37:05.633
No. Didn't make it.

37:09.300 --> 37:10.300
Give it another shot.

37:12.567 --> 37:13.567
I just missed it.

37:14.733 --> 37:17.167
Broke a few more braches off.
Lighten it up a little bit.

37:17.600 --> 37:20.233
See if I can get it out over
the duck.

37:22.333 --> 37:24.400
Yes! I'm gonna
get it this time.

37:24.500 --> 37:26.567
There it goes. Snagged it.

37:28.833 --> 37:30.400
Got my duck.

37:31.267 --> 37:32.833
Another shoveler.

37:32.900 --> 37:34.367
A male. That's what I wanted.

37:35.567 --> 37:37.600
Duck hunting's good today.

37:37.700 --> 37:39.200
Couldn't ask for a better day.

37:44.133 --> 37:45.867
Got my three ducks.

37:46.533 --> 37:48.500
Looks all right for now.

37:48.567 --> 37:49.833
(SIGHS)

37:49.900 --> 37:51.167
Cook 'em kind
of long and slow.

37:54.500 --> 37:56.500
Look at those beautiful ducks.

37:56.567 --> 37:58.500
Oh, yeah those are done.

37:58.567 --> 38:00.700
The only meat
I've had for a while has been
dried caribou meat.

38:00.767 --> 38:02.700
This is the first fresh meat
I've eaten in some time.

38:04.000 --> 38:05.033
Mm.

38:07.000 --> 38:08.933
I mean what better place
to have dinner,

38:09.000 --> 38:10.233
than right beside the lake

38:10.300 --> 38:11.933
that I walked around
to find these ducks?

38:14.433 --> 38:16.367
Mm, it was a beautiful day.

38:26.433 --> 38:28.633
SUE: Well, the world is circle
and it turns around and round.

38:28.700 --> 38:31.333
Things change,
things evolve, things rotate.

38:36.200 --> 38:38.367
The journey of getting Kavik
back up and running.

38:38.433 --> 38:43.833
I want to get the mass done
rather than all the tiny
little chores.

38:44.700 --> 38:46.733
Finished getting
all the freezers out.

38:47.200 --> 38:50.233
But now,
I've got a whole winter's
worth of garbage to burn.

38:52.967 --> 38:56.267
This is, uh, this is just
another chore on the list.

39:00.700 --> 39:04.533
I mean it's like anywhere,
you know,
sweetie baby honey do-list.

39:04.600 --> 39:06.600
Take out the garbage.

39:06.667 --> 39:09.867
Only problem is I'm my own
sweetie baby honey do.

39:09.933 --> 39:13.200
This is the Sue-do list.
The honey-Sue list.

39:14.467 --> 39:16.400
So these are the cigarettes.

39:16.467 --> 39:19.267
Um, to do the work
the doctor did,

39:19.333 --> 39:21.500
I had to quit smoking.

39:21.567 --> 39:25.033
So, and he told me the gravity
of the situation.

39:25.100 --> 39:27.567
And that it was, ah,

39:27.633 --> 39:29.533
the necessity of the surgery
was life or death.

39:29.600 --> 39:31.600
He wouldn't do it if I smoked.

39:31.667 --> 39:33.367
Put out the cigarette before
I walked into his office,

39:33.433 --> 39:34.433
haven't had one since.

39:35.600 --> 39:37.900
Come on.
I'm serious about quitting.

39:37.967 --> 39:39.600
So I'm burning
all the cigarettes that I had.

39:44.800 --> 39:46.367
Bye, cigarettes!

39:47.933 --> 39:50.033
You're gonna
have to smoke without me.

40:02.433 --> 40:03.833
Ah! Who the foxy?

40:04.733 --> 40:06.533
Who's my little foxy!

40:06.867 --> 40:08.800
Who is that? Is that Slinky?

40:08.867 --> 40:11.200
It took Slinky a day
to figure out that I was here.

40:11.700 --> 40:12.800
Come on.

40:12.867 --> 40:15.067
Slinky and Ermie
were best buddies.

40:15.667 --> 40:17.433
Um, they would,
Slinky would beak on the side

40:17.500 --> 40:18.733
of the tent every morning.

40:18.800 --> 40:20.667
And Ermie would beak back
on the window.

40:20.733 --> 40:21.833
And they would come out
and play.

40:22.567 --> 40:26.100
Because of Ermie's
health condition,
um, she's got to stay in town.

40:26.600 --> 40:28.867
And is now living
in town permanently.

40:28.933 --> 40:31.500
So, I don't have
a little friend here any more .

40:35.367 --> 40:38.800
Don't want to get emotional,
but it means
a lot to me to have the foxes.

40:39.433 --> 40:41.167
Yuck! Come on, dummy, come on.

40:42.800 --> 40:43.967
(WHISTLES) Come on.

40:44.400 --> 40:45.633
Come in.

40:48.033 --> 40:52.933
It's good to be back. I mean,
that the amount of work
I have to do is astounding.

40:53.567 --> 40:55.667
Um, I'm gonna
have to be creative.

40:55.733 --> 41:00.067
Uh, I have a 10-pound
weight restriction,
for the foreseeable future.

41:02.567 --> 41:05.333
Honestly I need to take
this entire summer,

41:07.000 --> 41:10.133
and assess how well I can do
my job.

41:10.200 --> 41:11.567
Am I done?

41:11.633 --> 41:13.967
And the answer is,
I don't know.

41:19.800 --> 41:22.767
JESSIE: When you're in Alaska,
you work until the sun
goes down.

41:28.900 --> 41:32.667
NARRATOR: After repairing
his boat and successfully
getting it to shore,

41:32.733 --> 41:34.700
Jessie must launch his vessel
into the water

41:34.767 --> 41:39.000
and test its durability
before he can begin
his summer fishing season.

41:48.033 --> 41:49.933
(EXCLAIMS) Yeah!

41:50.000 --> 41:51.367
Time to get
the summer started!

41:52.400 --> 41:54.167
Yeah, we really
got it easy, you know?

41:54.233 --> 41:57.467
These old timers,
they just figured
everything out.

41:57.533 --> 41:59.867
Poling up rivers,

41:59.933 --> 42:02.333
pulling their dogs,
boats out with dogs.

42:03.300 --> 42:05.800
When I do this kind of stuff,
it's like I'm living
in the past.

42:06.767 --> 42:08.367
I think I was born
100 years too late.

42:12.967 --> 42:15.967
I hadn't been out on the river
since the ice flowed,
you know?

42:16.033 --> 42:19.400
So, I'd been out with other
people in their boats,
but this is my boat.

42:19.467 --> 42:22.367
And now I can go take care
of my jobs,
I gotta do out here.

42:25.333 --> 42:27.867
I'm gonna start putting up
some food
for my dogs and myself.

42:27.933 --> 42:29.900
I miss that taste
of that fresh fish.

42:33.567 --> 42:36.000
I guess this is the bonus
of living right next
to the river.

42:36.067 --> 42:37.967
All my stuff's close
for getting down here.

42:38.033 --> 42:40.433
Get to take the pleasure
of doing
a lot of this stuff by hand.

42:45.333 --> 42:48.300
The motor's running.
That's a good sign.

42:48.367 --> 42:49.967
Go upriver,
see how the boat's running.

42:53.400 --> 42:54.400
Woo!

42:55.833 --> 42:58.567
Wow, it's absolutely
beautiful out here.

43:01.000 --> 43:03.767
Getting on the river
is pretty much the peak point

43:03.833 --> 43:05.433
of happiness for me
in the summer.

43:10.267 --> 43:12.300
You just feel so free
when you're out on the river.

43:12.367 --> 43:13.867
It's an indescribable feeling.

43:14.200 --> 43:15.667
Words don't really
do justice to it.

43:17.000 --> 43:19.700
Now I got a lot of work to do,
but it's all work
I want to do.

43:19.967 --> 43:22.600
If you're out here,
it's hard for it to seem
like hard work.
